<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-122-320 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 057 035</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  June 26 1991 n1559 p24(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Chinese transfer a success. (Dysan Magnetics and DysanInternational move California floppy-disk assembly facility toZhuhai, China) (includes a related article on the importance ofHong Kong)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Elliott, Mick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>When Hanny Magnetics of Hong Kong acquired the California XidexGroup in 1990, the responsibility for running the company fell onits subsidiaries Dysan Magnetics and Dysan International.andP;  Xidex'sfloppy-disk assembly facility in California was moved to Zhuhai,China, at a cost of $2 million.andP;  The lower operating and laborcosts currently saves the company $40 million a year.andP;  Microfloppy disks are assembled by hand by young Chinese girls that arepaid $50 per month, an amount set by the Chinese government.andO;There is fierce competition for these jobs, which can double aselected employee's income, and special examinations are required.andO;The company feels it can meet 15 percent to 20 percent of theworld's demand and, while they are not planning to begin a pricewar, they have room to negotiate if prices begin to plummet.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dysan International (Location).andO;Topic:     Facility LocationFloppy diskChina.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>